y, including the League of Nations and Bank for International Settlements, created after World War I. These institutions endowed civil servants, bankers, and colonial authorities from Europe and the United States with extraordinary powers: to enforce austerity, coordinate the policies of independent central banks, oversee development programs, and regulate commodity prices. In a highly unequal world, they faced a new political challenge: was it possible to reach into sovereign states and empires to intervene in domestic economic policies without generating a backlash? Martin follows the intense political conflicts provoked by the earliest international efforts to govern capitalism—from Weimar Germany to the Balkans, Nationalist China to colonial Malaya, and the Chilean desert to Wall Street. The Meddlers shows how the fraught problems of sovereignty and democracy posed by institutions like the IMF are not unique to late twentieth-century globalization, but instead first emerged during an earlier period of imperial competition, world war, and economic crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapitalismxHistoryy20th century. 0aEconomic councilsxHistoryy20th century. 0aEconomic historyy1918-. 0aInternational financexHistoryy20th century. 0aSovereigntyxEconomic aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xEconomic aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aBretton Woods.  aBritish Empire.  aCentral Bank Independence.  aConditional Lending.  aGlobal capitalism.  aGreat Depression.  aHistory of capitalism.  aInternational Development.  aInternational Monetary Fund.  aLeague of Nations.  aNeo-liberalism.  aStructural Adjustment.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2022 Englishz978311099282308iTitle is 